<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 91-08-01 - Suppression of Electromagnetic Devices</stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi910801" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>91-08-01</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>July, 1991</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>ELECTRICAL</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Suppression of Electromagnetic Devices</subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>Electromagnetic devices used in International vehicles include relays, magnetic switches,
                    solenoids, electronic injectors and air conditioning compressor clutches. When the current in the
                    actuating coil is switched OFF in such devices, the collapsing magnetic field creates a momentary
                    NEGATIVE voltage spike which can be as high as 600 volts (see Note) This energy jumps the gap
                    between the contacts in the switch controlling the electromagnetic device, generating electrical
                    "noise."
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108011">(Figure 1</hotlnk>and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108012">Figure 2.</hotlnk>)
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>This phenomena is also the basis for the design of ignition coils used in spark ignition
                            engines, except that they are specially designed to generate 1000's of volts.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f9108011" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9108011.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Switch For Electromagnetic Device Closed</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f9108012" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9108012.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2. Switch For Electromagnetic Device Being Opened</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. DISCHARGE ARC</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. LARGE NEGATIVE VOLTAGE BEING CREATED</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>Electronic devices such as instruments and clusters, electronic engine and transmission controls
                    and other customer added electronic equipment may be damaged or may not operate as expected when
                    subjected to this "noise".
                </para>
                <para>The electronic instruments and clusters and other electronic devices used in International
                    vehicles are designed to screen out as much of this "noise" as possible. However, because of the
                    many types of "noise," this screening may not always be 100% effective. Therefore, Navistar is
                    incorporating suppression into the electromagnetic devices used in its vehicles. In order to protect
                    both Navistar and customer installed electronic devices,
                    <emph type="bold">NAVISTAR STRONGLY RECOMMENDS THAT BODY AND EQUIPMENT INSTALLERS SPECIFY AND
                        INSTALL ONLY ELECTRICALLY SUPPRESSED ELECTROMAGNETIC DEVICES</emph>.
                </para>
                <para>To suppress the unwanted voltage spikes, a diode (or special resistor) is installed across the
                    actuating coil as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108013">Figure 3</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9108013" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9108013.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3. Magnetic Switch With Diode</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. DIODE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. MAGNETIC SWITCH</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>In the circuit shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108013">Figure 3</hotlnk>, the diode "shorts out" the negative voltage generated
                    when the switch is opening. Consequently, there is no high negative voltage generated, no arcing at
                    the switch and therefore no noise transmitted into the electrical system. To suppress an
                    electromagnetic device, simply add a diode as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108013">Figure 3</hotlnk>, noting the correct polarity. The "banded" end of the
                    diode connects to the positive or plus (+) side of the circuit as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9108014">Figure 4</hotlnk>. The diode will "blow" if installed backwards or if
                    battery polarity is accidentally reversed. Diode trade numbers 1N4005 (preferred) or 1N4004 are
                    inexpensive and readily available at electronic supply stores.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9108014" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G9108014.webp" type="webp" resolution="300"/>
                    <caption>Figure 4. Diode (1N4005 or 1N4004)</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. DIODE BAND</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <para>In addition, Navistar has available the following relay and magnetic switches with built-in
                    suppression.
                </para>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
